 These differences in sentence length compound, leaving the U.S. with many more prisoners than elsewhere in the world.  
</p>

<p>
Parole, or community supervision for low risk offenders, has been proposed as the solution to the U.S.’s large prison population.  Although seemingly a compassionate policy, parole has become a major contributor to recidivism, or re-incarceration.  Because parole extends individuals’ experiences with the criminal justice system, those on parole are often sent back to prison for minor violations like missing curfew, associating with others convicted of a crime, or missing a meeting with their parole officer.  A 2016 study found that 4 out of 10 people incarcerated in the U.S. were on parole at the time of arrest, many for only technical violations
